********************************************************************************
// SECTION 6 Volatility
********************************************************************************


// Exercise 1 {Modelling volatility in US yields}


**********************************************
webuse "yields.dta", clear

tsset obs , daily
replace obs = td(04oct1988)+_n-1

// 1. ARCH(2)
//See page 449, Brooks for testing ARCH models

* First regress the independent variable on a constant.
qui reg dr3m
* Next implement the ARCH test.
estat archlm, lags(2)

qui reg dr1y
estat archlm, lags(2)

qui reg dr3y
estat archlm, lags(2)

qui reg dr5y
estat archlm, lags(2)

qui reg dr7y
estat archlm, lags(2)

qui reg dr10y
estat archlm, lags(2)
* All the chi2 statistics and p-values are the same as those given in Table 3.
* The results suggest that there is autocorrelation (in the second lag) for all these time series.

// 2. GARCH(1,1)
qui arch dr3m, arch(1) garch(1)	// Refer to slide 15 of lecture handout.
								// -arch (1)- corresponds to q
								// -garch(1)- corresponds to p
est store dr3m
qui arch dr1y, arch(1) garch(1)
est store dr1y
qui arch dr3y, arch(1) garch(1)
est store dr3y
qui arch dr5y, arch(1) garch(1)
est store dr5y
qui arch dr7y, arch(1) garch(1)
est store dr7y
qui arch dr10y, arch(1) garch(1)
est store dr10y

est table dr3m dr1y dr3y dr5y dr7y dr10y, t title ("Garch(1,1)")
* "arch L1."  gives the estimate for alpha_1
* "garch L1." gives the estimate for beta_1
* The constant in the ARCH section is alpha_0
* The other constant is gamma_0

* The results for dr3y, dr5y, dr7y and dr10y are almost identical to those in Table 4.
* The estimates for constant terms for dr3m and dr1y are different (decimals in different places) but t-stats are the same.


// 3. GARCH-M
// Not covered in lectures, but steps can be found at http://www.stata.com/manuals13/tsarch.pdf
arch dr3m, archm arch(1) garch(1) archmexp(sqrt(X))
est store garchm


**********************************************


// Exercise 2 {Foreign Exchange Market Volatility}


**********************************************
webuse "hours.dta", clear

// 1. Compute returns
tsset obs, daily
g retbp = log(bp)-log(L1.bp)
g retdm = log(dm)-log(L1.dm)

// 2. Test for ARCH(1) and ARCH(2)
qui reg retbp
estat archlm, lags(1 2)

qui reg retdm
estat archlm, lags (1 2)
* P-value = 0.0000
* There are ARCH(1) and ARCH(2) effects in the BP and DM exchange rates

// 3.(a)
arch retbp , arch(1) garch(1)
predict hbp, variance			// For question 4.
arch retdm, arch(1) garch(1)
predict hdm, variance			// For question 4.
// (b) and (c) not covered in lecture

// 4. Plot conditional variance against actual squared returns
// Generate the squared returns
g retbp2 = retbp^2
g retdm2 = retdm^2
// Plot the graphs (and combine, if you wish)
twoway (tsline retbp2) (tsline hbp), name(pl_bp)
twoway (tsline retdm2) (tsline hdm), name(pl_dm)
graph combine pl_bp pl_dm


**********************************************


// Exercise 3 {Modelling Volatility of the S&P Index}


**********************************************
// Data file not available
**********************************************


// Exercise 4 {Time varying risk in the Australian term structure}


**********************************************
// Data file not available

// Exercise 5 {Leverage effects in Equity Markets}


**********************************************
// Data file not available
**********************************************


// Exercise 6 {Equity returns}


**********************************************
webuse "equity.dta", clear
* Note there are 4952 observations, not 4953 as stated in the question.
* Note also that the variables appear to be the percentage returns, not the actual stock index values.
tsset datevec

// 1. Estimate unconditional distribution
kdensity ftse, normal title ("Kernel Density - FTSE")
kdensity dow, normal title ("Kernel Density - Dow")
kdensity nk, normal title ("Kernel Density - Nikkei")

// 2. Compute daily percentage returns and test for ARCH
qui reg ftse
estat archlm, lags(1 2 3)
qui reg dow
estat archlm, lags(1 2 3)
qui reg nk
estat archlm, lags(1 2 3)
* All three indices exhibit ARCH(1), ARCH(2) and ARCH(3).

// 3. Estimate GARCH(1,1)
arch ftse, arch(1) garch(1)
est store ftse
predict hftse, variance

arch dow, arch(1) garch(1)
est store dow
predict hdow, variance

arch nk, arch(1) garch(1)
est store nk
predict hnk, variance
